 policies in Australia targeted those who were least integrated socially and culturally, and who enjoyed fewer legitimate economic opportunities. Amidst intense political debate, struggle, and conflict, new forces were unleashed as a post-settler colonial state grappled with its past. Morris provides a social analysis of the ensuing effects of neoliberal policy and the way indigenous rights were subsequently undermined by this emerging new political orthodoxy in the 1990s.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAboriginal AustraliansxCivil rightszAustraliazNew South WalesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAboriginal AustraliansxGovernment relationszAustraliazNew South WalesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAboriginal AustraliansxLand tenurezAustraliazNew South WalesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAboriginal AustralianszAustraliazNew South WalesxGovernment relationsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAboriginal Australians, Treatment ofzAustraliazNew South WalesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNeoliberalismzAustraliazNew South WalesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPostcolonialismzAustraliazNew South WalesxHistoryy20th century. 0aProtest movementszAustraliazNew South WalesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRiotszAustraliazNew South WalesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311099823840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238538740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782385387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782385387/original  a978-3-11-099823-8  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA